titleStmt.title: Beginning of Mac Vurich’s Panegyrick on the Macleans

note.p: The context for this is as follows: The upper half of p.176 reads "This poem [The MacVurich Panegyrick on the MacLeans] was composed, at least, thirty Years before Kennedy’s book was published. All these laid together would seem to argue the Genuineness of these Catalogues preserved among the Macleans, and, although MacVurich in hope of a reward should be included to forge an illustrious and antient descent for those he designed to flatter, Yet I see no Reason That Doctor Kennedy a Stranger to them writing in a forreign country should do so, or make any mention of them at all, if he had not found in some record worthy of credit that they were so descended. There has been in all ages a friendship ‘twixt the MacKenzies and MacLeans and among them both a received tradition of their being descended of two brothers. But I could never find any authority for this or any seeming probability even from those who affirmed it most. Mr Buchanan of Aichinar makes mention of it, and supposes the Macleans to be descended of the Gerald Earl of Kildarr, and I have heared that Doctor George MacKenzie in his genealogy of the MacKenzies affirms some such matter. But as Mr Buchanan gives no voucher, and the Doctor’s book has not appeared in the world, and the forementioned tradition has few vouchers, and yet fewer that gives it credit, I am always more apt to believe the most received and better vouched tradition above related; Yet, if the Doctor's book proves the fraternity from better authority, I yield to reason."
This is the first of a number of instances where the -c of Mac/Mhic has been combined with the second element in this text. In other texts "mac Raith" is to be found.
The 1467 MS has “suthain” at this point (fol. 1re45)). It is possible, therefore, that “Milhun” may be a rendering of “Maoil Shuthain."
=Aonghas Uallach. However, where we get "Aonghas" and "uallach" appearing in Genealogies it is usually "Aonghus son of Ferghus Aulaidh or Uallach".
